Author: @Ruba327
Comment:
This is my personal interpretation of Escapeâ€”a story that reached deep into my heart and stayed there. Thank you, Chan and Hyunjin, for creating something so raw, powerful, and true.
After watching Escape multiple times and reflecting deeplyâ€”while also listening to othersâ€™ takesâ€”I felt compelled to share what I saw and felt in my heart.

Escape is a profound visual metaphor for breaking free from societal expectations, internal pain, and the pressure to conform. The openingâ€”Chan and Hyunjin butting heads like wild animalsâ€”quickly shifts to both being chained. Yet each breaks free, returning to their truest selves: Chan moving like a wolf, and Hyunjin swift and stealthy, like a ferret.

They meet again and fightâ€”at first seriously, then playfully, as the fight transforms into companionship. This brings them closer to their true selves, symbolized by paw prints in the sand instead of footprints. During Chanâ€™s high-pitched vocal moment, they stare into a fish tankâ€”symbolic of beauty trapped, observed, and contained, just like themselves. Chan breaks the glass and hands Hyunjin a dagger-like shard. Itâ€™s not a weaponâ€”itâ€™s a symbol of trust and survival. Chan rests his head on Hyunjin in protective love, while Hyunjin looks unhingedâ€”care and chaos in stark contrast.

Chan watches over Hyunjin as the latter unleashes his pent-up emotions. At 1:43 (possibly referencing â€œCASE 143â€), Chan sees black, inky shadow-hands pressed against a windowâ€”souls trapped, begging for freedom. Sensing danger, he grabs Hyunjin and runs. They hide, but Hyunjin breaks down and runs off, dagger in hand.

Chan panics. Hyunjin is shown imprisoned againâ€”crouched, terrified, desperate, and alone. Chan, separately, is bound not by chains, but by grief and guilt. When he howls at the moon, both their chains breakâ€”itâ€™s a spiritual rescue.

They run toward each otherâ€”Hyunjin desperate, Chan smiling. A flash of a white ferret and black wolf confirms they are truly themselves. They embrace, and then we see them in fur coats that match their animals.

Then they face the eerie truckâ€”its blinding lights symbolizing surveillance, fame, and oppression. Chan looks afraidâ€”for Hyunjin. But Hyunjinâ€™s defiance gives him strength. They clasp hands, charge forwardâ€”glass shatters. Liberation.

A masterpiece of authenticity, protection, and shared freedom. The story of Stray Kidsâ€”and of everyone seeking their voice in this world.

Author: @sousouchiboub7364
Comment:
Okey, Chan and Hyunjin appear to be jumping from what looks like a wall as if they've escaped from somewhere. It seems like they're fighting each other, which I don't think is entirely accurate. Then, we see Hyunjin cutting the red threads that tie him in "red lights", symbolizing liberation and escape.

One of the interesting things is that there's a scene that resembles the one in 'Red Lights.' The second 0:52 looks like the scene from "Red Lights" In the second 0:21 There are many hints and references to the previous song. It appears that they've managed to escape from whoever or whatever was holding them captive in 'Red Lights.' We see how their fight turns into playfulness and laughter in the bed scene, where we see a part of the 'Red Lights' clip. The restraints that once controlled them are now broken and they become free to celebrate their freedom.

Everything seems fascinating to them because it's their first time experiencing the outside world. The scene where Chan breaks the glass and gives the shard to Hyunjin has multiple interpretations, but I won't deny that my initial thought was that it symbolized ending the pain if it was the only option left. But no cause in 1:46 we see that Chan did everything to protect Hyunjin.

Then, we see how they destroy everything in their path, symbolizing their rebellion against that world. However, those 'monsters' (the haunting thoughts, desires, and temptations) continue to pursue them. Hyunjin, who chooses to fight and sacrifice himself instead of escaping, gets captured again. It may seem overly dramatic, but I couldn't help but connect his captivity in the song to his hiatus from the group's activities in 2021.

Chan appears desperate, unable to save Hyunjin, but ultimately, they manage to overcome their struggles and reunite. The scene where they run towards each other and hugging is one of the most beautiful moments in the video.

There are also multiple references to werewolves throughout the video, from the footprints to the full moon and the reddened moon, followed by the appearance of werewolves in the scene where they run towards each other. It was breathtaking.

I'd like to mention that in 2:48 when the image from this scene was released, many people interpreted it as a sign of control as if one of them was running away from the other and wouldn't be able to escape. However, upon watching the video and seeing the context of the scene, it became clear that Chan's grip on the chain wasn't a form of control, but rather a sign of fear - fear of losing Hyunjin again.

At that moment, as they face the car, Hyunjin's expression seems normal, while Chan's face is filled with fear and desperation. Ultimately, if they have to face something, they'll face it together. The ending seems open, leaving room for interpretation. Perhaps the car doesn't contain enemies, but rather the other members who have come to rescue them.

Keep in mind that my analysis is purely speculative, and I'm discussing Chan and Hyunjin from a fraternal perspective.
Long way to say I'm in loveâ¤ğŸ–¤

They represent two sides of the same person and uniting a passionate crazy side and calmer responsible reasoning side. AN INTERPRETATION.

They encounter each other with some conflict, running in the same direction but also hindering/opposing each other, then they struggle directly but enjoy it and realize they like each other, one side is happy goofing around and the other watching/protecting from above, notices the threat/obstacle and wants to get away, tries to subdue the crazy side (hand over mouth), but the crazy side decides act up and is locked away, calm side is left separated and missing the other, calls to a mutual inspiration/purpose that binds them together and they both respond to (moon), which gives them power, and then they chose unite as one person (the embrace) realizing they are more powerful/better united together, and finally they encounter the obstacle, and instead of the reasoning side leading the way, he drops the chain and hold hands with his crazy side to face it together and attack it head on utilizing both sides equally.

Author: @juliahwangg
Comment:
Plot of the Escape MV
Bang Chan and Hyunjin are werewolves
We see paw prints on the ground. They move like wolves.
They live in solitude, hiding from everyone
Bang Chan is the eldest, he has accepted himself. Hyunjin is the youngest. He still cannot accept his werewolf nature
Previously, during the full moon, Hyunjin chained himself up and was afraid of the transformation
Bang Chan always tried to protect him. He taught him how to defend himself and fight
But this time, everything went differently. The full moon and the approaching shadows symbolize the oncoming transformation
At first, Bang Chan grabs Hyunjin's hand and runs to hide him, as always
But Hyunjin frees his nature, he is tired of hiding, he runs, he is ready
Bang Chan running towards him and smiling widely. He is happy that Hyunjin finally let himself go
They both turn into wolves

Comment:
Call me crazy, but I have a theory that these 4 Mixtape M/Vs are actually an apocalyptic series ğŸ¤¯
1. It started with Changbin and I.N living in utopian world and taking part in a real-life video game full of life threating acrobatics (like an Black Mirror episode), trying to win money/trophy. They need to win no matter what it takes and how much it's tiring. They're BURNING TIRES and tyres. We seem them trying to navigate through the game while being observant to others (like that caterpillar). After winning they returned to their regular life, only to be punished for a speeding ticket.
2. Then Han and Felix's world showed underworld in a cult society. They had to be true to themselves, they had to be TRU MAN, and their liberation from prison pushed that society to anarchy and destruction.
3. Chan and Hyunjin now play a pair in world on fire - crazy times, where only being together keeps them sane and gives them energy to finally ESCAPE from everyone that wants to hurt them.
Prediction 4. CINEMA will be about Lee Know and Seungmin living in a dystopian society, hoping to find little pieces of happiness in the world that remains and them reminiscing about their past lives, feeling like their life was a movie, an absolute CINEMA.

Again, call me crazy. I rarely do mental gymnastics so this idea surprised me. Anyways, all the songs are masterpieces and I can't wait to hear them live ğŸ¤—

Author: @llemon-u6h
Comment:
4am thoughts
someone mentioned that hyunjin is a white ferret & chan is black/grey wolf, so I watch the mv again with that pov. at the beginning of the mv it shows that hyunjin is on his own & kind of 'wild'. and it looks like chan is preying on/searching for something. but then he found hyunjin & maybe he 'adopt & tame' him (the part where chan pushed hyujin against the glass etc) until hyunjin become gentle. they started become close, like brothers, playing around together. the part where chan gives hyunjin a piece of glass might indicate like weapon to protect himself or sth im not really sure about this part.

at the part 'escape this reality.. ill fulfil your fantasies' chan was smiling while looking at hyunjin who was having fun by himself (i love this part so much cs it portray like pure innocent joy). chan here looks like a guardian or protector keeping watch over hyunjin.

but then he sensed danger coming & quickly grabbed hyunjin to hide. but hyunjin take the weapon, the glass, and charged towards the 'danger', leaving chan behind. hyunjin might be captured by the 'danger' (the part where hyunjin was alone in a room with metal chains around his body). chan proceed to hide & wanting to rescue hyunjin, he 'summon the full moon' to get powers (i think hshshsh) and the part where the chains on hyunjin started floating, maybe answering the call of chan's power (I'm making my own theory here haha) & he succeed to escape from the danger (where he and chan finally reunited & hug).

then, the danger (the truck) comes again & hyunjin and chan holding hands showing that they will fight & escape from the danger together.

this is my interpretation of the mv. could be very wrong tho hahaha.

ps: when someone mentioned about the ferret & wolf, i was imagining a real ferret & wolf (maybe jiniret and wolfchan) playing tgt and it was so cute i couldn't get the picture out of my mindâ¤

Chan gives Hyun the piece of broken glass as if offering him a way out, but after an internal struggle, he chooses Chan instead. An enemy appears and they join hands, choosing to bind themselves, choosing to escape together.

Author: @NoorShafiya2004
Comment:
I honestly feel like crying cus this kind of gives me a feeling that this talks about toxic relationships.

Like bangchan saying in return for this pain, give yourself to me. Like hes saying he'll inflict pain as a reward for hyunjin always making himself available. Like kind if punishing him for being a victim. But making it seem like love.

And the references to red lights in the mattress scene when theyre happy and playing around is like showing that underneath all those happy moments, the abuse is waiting to happen. Cus red lights kinda talks about going into the deep end of your temptations.

The scene where bangchan gives hyunjin the piece of glass is like him giving him a piece of his vulnerability.

Also the scene where they run, you can see bangchan cover hyunjins mouth. Silencing him, like how abusers silence their victims (usually under the guise of protecting them) and then hyunjin runs away with chans vulnerability.

The scene of hyunjin alone, it seems like hes trying to cut the chains off using chans vulnerability (the piece of glass)
And bangchan is kinda like looking for him because abusers also depend on their victims so bangchan is looking for him desperately.

And then finally its like the chains are dragging them back to each other. And the hug is very emotional as its them reuniting after a falling out. And then its like when theyre running to each other you can see theyre potrayed in like an animalistic form. Kinda like the bond is animalistic and primal with each other.
After they reunite you can see the truck, its like the outsiders and the headlights are kinda like them exposing their toxicity. And theyre deciding to fight against it together. (Shown by charging against it) Kinda shows how both the abuser and victim of toxic relationships defend their "love"

Its also the overall references...like chasing each other. Being violent towards each other. Being playful. The occasional tender moments. The chains. And the first scene where they run and one kicks the barrel of fire that turns everything red. Kinda like showing how its when one hurts the other that the flaws in their relationship are brought out (shown by turning red) and then the lyrics saying how you can free the chains and shackles whenever you want. Kinda how you can logically leave a toxic relationship if you want but its actually not that easy.

Hyunjin describing chan as a devil by the phrase "devils gestures" saying theres so many reasons to be ruined by him (like how victims usually find reasons to stay with their abusers)

Hyunjin saying he'd burn himself to melt away chan's coldness (cold-heartness...kinda like the I can fix him vibe that toxic relationships give)

Also the scene where hyunjin kinda goes psycho with the breaking the shopping cart and everything and chan admiring it kinda shows how the narcissist kinda influences 5he victim to the point that they'd pick up their narcissistic and abusive ways as well.

That scene following the scene where chan gives him his vulnerability (the glass piece) shows the closeness they reach before hyunjin decided to run away and then they reunite.Ultimately showing that the vicious cycle continues.

After reuniting, you can see in the shot of their hands . It seems as if theyre chained together again. But when you look closer ,you can see channie is holding hyunjinnie's chain. Kinda showing how the abuser once again has the victim in their control.

I just love the depth of the song, lyrics ,beat and the metophorical scenes in this MV.

Just speaks to me as a person who's been in a toxic relationship.

Thank you bangchan and hyunjin for this beautiful masterpiece and for making me feel heard. â¤â¤â¤â¤

Author: @chukovskaya
Comment:
I've already read many theories and interpretations of Escape. Dramatic, erotic, fantasy, highly social, etc. But for me, the clip is not about the romantic part of love at all. It's about the great relief that "you and I are of the same blood" and "I'm not alone."

A man lives, keeps a "wolf" in himself. There's another one, with a smaller predator inside. Maybe each of them thought that he was the only one in the world who was completely different from the others, "wrong", lonely - but then they found each other. They found out. And they didn't scare each other off. And the chains of restraint and mimicry under the "norm" have broken, because there is no longer any need to hold back and pretend. No point to hide the real face and the view of the world. Fun, crazy, free. Together. Maybe for the first time in his lifes. And they're either being chased or followed. Whether it's public opinion with censure, or the Winchester brothers with stern faces. Chan wants to protect and hide, Hwang wants to protect and drive everyone away. And then one rushes into a fight, while the other, meanwhile, is looking for shelter - and misses the moment when the smaller one rushes. So far, Chan have climbed up to figure out where to look - Hwang is already on a chain, pining, in a damp dungeon. He shakes violently and squeezes a piece of glass. And when the X-Files started altogether and the chains took off by themselves, both rushed to save the other. All at once, without hesitation. And these hugs are also a huge relief, "I'm in time"!

And there - the headlights, the fever in the blood, the hand in the hand and the look "Together?" - "To the end!" And - fighting. They will find out about victory or defeat later, the main thing is that they will no longer give up and will not hide.

And it's the kind of story that makes my heart beat faster. Finding each other and being on the same side is priceless.

I love this clip.

When they run, they run like an arrow, when they play, they are fast and slick, if they attack, they throw all their body in, and once they clawed in, can take down a much larger enemy. But when threatened they can resort back to burrowing. And the thing with burrows is they only have one way in and no way out. So if the threat chases you down and waits at the door, you can't leave. That at least until someone distracts it. Maybe someone you've played with before

Author: @melody1953
Comment:
So they're sort of werewolves/just wolves/have wolf form power, and they might be connected in a way, based on how they reacted when Hyunjin decided to head towards the danger (it looked like he was trying to protect Chan/let him escape TT or at least find an way out of the trap situation) and Chris climbed up the tour using or awakening their powers through/against the red light of the moon. It looks like Chan was struggling when the red light shone upon him, but then he tried to control it with his hand/power and a red moon formed or got revealed from the darkness. Then, Hyunjin felt something happening and he lifted his hand, and he noticed he lifted his chains too. So they decided to find each other again and face ahead what's blocking or chasing them. In the end, they escaped in a way or another, but fighting together. There's broken glass at the end, including the piece they had picked up to fight/defend themselves soooooooooooooooo I don't know. I don't wanna think they died or lost, so let's just stay on the fact they decided to face the danger together, holding hands.

After rewatching the mv, it's true they act a bit like wolves/animals playing together, not caring as much about the violence of their way of playing (as if they're tough enough to tank/endure the throwing around and all), rolling and climbing around, breaking thinks, etc. They also got interested in the gold fishes they found, but it might be because they were red and this color plays a role in this story. It might be why they smashed the fish tank down, to try to catch the fish as it's red. After breaking it, they don't find or grab any red fish, but they pick up a piece of the broken glass, finding a tool to fight or defend themselves if needed. It's like a step toward their freedom. The color red looks like is linked to what's chasing them, but also seems to be the key of either their way out or their powers.

Red Lights is the pull and the binding, whereas ESCAPE is the stage where they donâ€™t have to be shackled together to want to stay together.

But it could also be representative of two sides of someoneâ€™s personality or will. Red Lights is the attempt to restrain one side of yourself that youâ€™re ashamed of while ESCAPE is the acceptance of that side.

Phenomenal and deep work as always, wow.

Author: @Sikhindu
Comment:
There's so much going on in the video.

Without the lyrics I see two guys constantly fighting each other and life's obstacles, while going in the same direction. They have chains that match but it's not until the end when they chose to connect those chains and face the obstacles as one team rather than alone.

With the lyrics, I see two guys struggling with the drabness of life and offering each other a safe haven to take a break from it all. The lyrics say to take off the chains, meaning feel free to be one's self while with each other, yet in the video they don't take the chains off, they use them to connect with each other.

They want to offer each other a place of peace, sort of life the eye of the storm. Everything else can be messy but the two of them want to create a home in each other.

Like they said, it's a more mature version of Red Lights and I agree. This is more about the full spectrum of a relationship rather than just few aspects of it like in Red Lights. I enjoy this upgrade.

Now just my take, it's kinda painful seeing them out there living like homeless and kinda fighting each other. I am glad the storming ended and they could finally be together sans the fighting.

There are so many metaphors in this video and in the lyrics, I have really enjoyed myself.

Also, the chains from Red Light carried over to Escape, and instead of the polished interiors that is in Red Lights, they are out here in the rough streets, in the dirty, rough, and real world.

Hyunjin and Bang Chan, I love you!

Comment: The references to wolf spirit and animalistic behaviors from both, from the start the way they ran and moved was more wolf like than human. In the abandoned factory each moved and betrayed none human behaviors as animals that had been chained and kept in the dark. when they escaped the aggressive behaviors were more dominate even with there interactions with each other. But it was almost joyous at time even though they were wresting with each other they were smiling that all this rage and angst was being set free finally. Toward the end even though they tried being apart they were stronger together. They way it appears as if they are one in the same whole, one the human side one the wolf, or that Chan is the Alpha and Hyunjin is eighter his Beta or part of his pack. I lean toward that they are part of the same pack and was separated   from the group and kept captive for whatever reason . The lyric can be taken many different ways with a dynamic of being of one person is dominate and has kept them chained to teach them be it mentally or physically or both but as time passes knows they wont leave. The lyric the chains your free to take them off and also In exchange for this pain can you promise to show your love for me everyday. Both can be taken as one party who holds the control know regardless the chains are always there that the other is submissive and loyal to them. they wont leave they will take the pain as a reward for they love they hold for the other. Their is so much you can take from both the lyrics and the visual concept of the mv. It was beautifully done and like redlights there is so many layers to it as a whole. Not just a sexy song though it can be taken in that way. But it is much deeper to it as you take in all the elements as a whole.

Author: @architectofmylife-04
Comment:
I am STUNNED!!!! There is so much happening in this music video. First of all, it looks like a really insane action movie. My interpretation: This song is about embracing all parts of yourself. Like a union within oneself. Light and dark, all coming together to become a more powerful, fearless version of yourself. The events in the MV are not chronological.
Chan represents the outer persona, the lighter side of your being, the side that you show to the world. Hyunjin is the darker aspect. The inner self that is rejected and hidden cause of shame and guilt.

In the beginning, you are scared and lost and shackled, you reject parts of yourselves for too long. You have no idea when that even started. Those parts remain shackled, but in pain, they keep knocking at your heart to get your attention (hyunjin, writhing, looking uncomfortable, being shackled in the dark, reaching out to the window). It starts to get noisy, the demon inside you starts acting like a maniac, breaking things, acting crazy and violent; your life starts crumbling (all the violent and psycho scenes, the opening lyrics). It gets to a point where you can't ignore the demon anymore, so you finally start looking at them, hanging out with them but it isn't easy. The demon is mad at you for ignoring it for so long, so he unleashes all of that violence on you (the fight scenes), it gets really crazy but gradually you start liking it, understanding each other, there are even moments of peace (the two of them hanging out silently, affectionately, looking at the piece of glasses, playfighting). Gradually, it starts dawning on you just how deeply trapped you have been (fishes in the aquarium), so you look at them but there's acceptance, warmth, SADNESS towards yourself like "Oh MY GOD why have I been so trapped, why didn't I notice at first, and so on". Finally, you can't take it... staying trapped is no longer an option cz your back is against the wall now (them being stuck against the shutter), you try to find a way but in the same direction (chan pushing the shutter, trying to open it so they can go and hide again) but the demon that you kept shackled for so long, it becomes your power and says "NO MORE" and runs towards the "danger/fear" headfirst. And the moment that happens, you become this BEAST of a person, ready for any challenge, any danger, anything! You realise you were the only one who kept you shackled and you were always free to break free of those shackles and chains. You realise you can escape. And when you do make that escape, it is not meek... You RUN, you RUN for your LIFE! because you cannot bear to spend it like how you did before. And that's where you have full acceptance of yourself (the running and the HUG!!!!) You become ONE with yourself. And now you are not scared of any shadows, or lights, or power... come what may... and you dive into it headfirst TOGETHER hand-in-hand... (they collide into the unknown truck) fearlessly.

Also, I think the first person in this song is the inner demon (hyunjin). It's the demon singing... I can't let you go, 'cause the world's about to break, just follow me, i will take the lead, in exchange of this pain will you love me every day?

AHHHHH it's so so so so beautiful! I am going crazy over this song and I can't wait for the making video!!!!! Anyway, this got too long. Let me know what you guys think, if you happen to read it all.
